Authentication.

Docker login prompts for a username and a password or token, and then stores the credentials in the docker config file, so subsequent pulls and pushes to that registry are authenticated automatically. With no registry named, login defaults to docker hub, and you name a host to log in elsewhere. There are non-interactive forms for scripts, and the safest of those feeds the token in through standard input rather than putting it on the command line where your shell history would capture it. And a logout forgets the stored credentials.

There is an important caution about how those credentials are stored by default. The config file holds an auths block with one entry per registry, and the auth field there is just a base-sixty-four encoding of your username and token. That is not secret storage. Base-sixty-four is trivially reversible, so anyone who reads that file has your credentials.

The right answer is a credential helper, which offloads storage to the operating system's keychain or a secret manager. There is a keychain helper on mac, a credential-manager helper on windows, and helpers backed by the secret service or a password store on linux. There are also cloud-specific helpers that mint short-lived tokens from your cloud identity. Once a helper is configured, the plaintext auth field disappears from the file and the helper holds the secret instead. For continuous integration, the same principle applies, with tightly scoped, regularly rotated per-registry tokens rather than passwords. Hard-coded passwords in continuous-integration scripts are the single most common docker security failure, so use tokens, scope them tightly, and rotate them.
